image.altText: The exterior of a white marble court building.

props.synopsis: A Canberra corrections officer is denied bail after allegedly attacking a man through his car window, pulling him out of the window and further assaulting him, then attempting to run him over in a car.

title.children: Corrections officer allegedly attacked man and tried to run him down after weeks of threats, court hears

image.altText: A concrete building reading "Law Courts of the Australian Capital Territory", with Australian, ACT and Aboriginal flag.

props.synopsis: A former Canberra teacher facing charges of alleged child sex abuse dating back to the 1990s is banned from going near any schools or being in the presence of children without an adult present.

title.children: Former Canberra teacher facing child sexual abuse charges barred from going near schools

image.altText: A man wearing a checked shirt standing in a vineyard.

props.synopsis: At Mount Majura Vineyard on the edge of Canberra, viticulturalist James Hopper is planting new grape varieties that can better cope with the effects of a changing climate.

title.children: Canberra winemakers planting new grape varieties that could become the wines of the future

image.altText: A concrete building with lettering above the entrance reading "Law Courts of the Australian Capital Territory".

props.synopsis: The suspected pipe bomb was allegedly found behind the dishwasher of the man's former marital home.

title.children: Man who threatened ex-partner with alleged pipe bomb and napalm denied bail

image.altText: Four younger women and non-binary people lean against a wall.

props.synopsis: After deciding to form a band while watching School of Rock, the band have won an ARIA award and shared the stage with Pearl Jam in the same week.

title.children: From a year 9 Canberra sleepover to sharing a stage with Pearl Jam: The rise of Teen Jesus and the Jean Teasers

image.altText: A machete and a sheath lying on a table.

props.synopsis: A 30-year-old Canberra man has lost a bid for bail, after he was charged with attempted murder in the wake of an alleged machete attack in September.

title.children: Man who allegedly severed victim's fingers in machete attack refused bail in Canberra

image.altText: An older man wearing a suit adorned with military medals looks stands in a military museum.

title.children: Friends and family criticise 'debacle' behind awarding Victoria Cross to Private Richard Norden

image.altText: Two men sit on a wooden crate holding cups of coffee, coffee equipment is shown in the background such as coffee grinders

props.synopsis: Mathew Hatcher and Lewis McKenzie started a coffee-roasting business in a small Australian town, motivated less by money and more by the excuse to taste rare and expensive beans. When they met a coffee-growing family from Colombia, the business would transform lives and form a "connection with the heart".

title.children: South Coast coffee roasters' 'terrible business model' would end up changing lives across continents

image.altText: Printed photo of a young girl and boy playing with action figures.

props.synopsis: Georgy Sides and her friends grew up with absent fathers who served their country in Afghanistan in the wake of September 11. Now they're sharing their stories of how Australia's commitment to a distant theatre of war altered their adolescence and shaped who they are today.

title.children: 'We could never build a relationship': Life when your dad is in the SAS

image.altText: A man with brown hair takes a selfie with grass and open space behind him

title.children: 'My husband of 36 years was a conman': Estranged wife of Kris Ridgway says his scams left her with a life sentence

image.altText: A female judge in a court room.

props.synopsis: The Northern Territory coroner has delivered her findings and recommendations from a landmark coronial inquiry into the domestic violence killings of four Aboriginal women in the territory. She's also announced she'll hold a second major inquiry into the issue.

title.children: NT coroner details 'extent of horror' in landmark DV inquest findings

image.altText: A woman voting at night at a cardboard polling booth

props.synopsis: The era of Baby Boomers as the dominant voting force in Australian politics is at an end and the impact will play out at the next federal election. If you listen carefully, you can already hear that politicians know the power and numbers have shifted to younger people.

title.children: Farewell Baby Boomers as Gen Z and Millennials become Australia's key voting force

image.altText: Emma McKeon smiles with four gold medals

title.children: 'I wanted to see what I was capable of and I did': Olympic great Emma McKeon announces her retirement

image.altText: Nathan Lyon holds his hand on his head while Usman Khawaja and Marnus Labuschagne stand nearby

props.synopsis: A champion Australian team may have had visions of glorious Ashes farewells next summer, but as India continues to make the hosts look second rate in Perth, those plans may need a dramatic rethink.

title.children: The end of an era is approaching for Australian cricket. Its best laid plans may need to be ripped up

image.altText: Action shot of Jelena Dokic fiercly preparing to return a serve

image.altText: A coat of arms on a mantle.

image.altText: A yellow flag that says "open home" flying off a yellow real estate sign advertising an auction.

image.altText: A Qantas plane on the tarmac.

image.altText: O'Neil and Albanese walk through the lower house chamber, looking serious.

It will be the last chance before the election for the government's proposals to co-purchase homes with first homebuyers, and offer tax incentives for developers to build more affordable rental apartments.

image.altText: A group of men hold their fists up with flags behind them.

image.altText: A close-up of a fire ant being held by tweezers.

title.children: These venomous pests can float on floodwaters, and thousands of nests have been found south of Brisbane

image.altText: Three men in a park, all looking solemn.

title.children: LGBTQIA+ groups removed from Facebook for posting links to mental health organisations

image.altText: Sun setting on large housing development.

image.altText: Exterior photos of a youth detention centre.

image.altText: A man in a yellow shirt holds a drone with surf life saving red and yellow decorations.

image.altText: Giant screen on the wall of the ASX, with large green numbers, showing the price of shares which have risen.

image.altText: An aerial image looking down on a number of canoes around rocks on the edge of a fast-moving river.

image.altText: A view of a town from the top of a hill with an Indigenous art piece of a man with a spear admiring the view.

props.synopsis: A lack of aged care facilities in WA's far north often means Indigenous elders have to leave their country and culture behind, but an aged care provider in Roebourne is helping them see out their final days.

title.children: Aged care centre recognised as the best in rural Australia. So what is it doing differently?

image.altText: A graphic showing a hand holding a wallet with money, and icons representing bills, shopping and a house.

props.synopsis: Millions of Australians are barely getting by financially, according to polling for the ABC's Q+A. And they give little credit to the federal government for helping out.

title.children: Cost-of-living pain, concerns for US ties: Australians deliver a 2024 report card

image.altText: A voter puts a Senate paper into a ballot box for the 2016 federal election.

props.synopsis: Labor says its proposal is about getting big money out of politics, but crossbenchers and Clive Palmer say they are shutting out competitors.

title.children: A re-run of the 2022 election reveals how Labor's new funding rules really work

image.altText: Mary Fowler applauds Matildas fans

image.altText: Red Bull driver Max Verstappen punches his fists and screams with excitement

image.altText: A man wearing a white shirt learning against a football post and holding a football.

image.altText: Zvi Kogan a man in glasses with a long beard.

image.altText: Large Aboriginal flag flying on city street with crowd in background

props.synopsis: For some Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people, receiving an Australian of the Year award can be used to draw attention to important issues. But others feel unable to accept a nomination because the timing of the awards is too painful.
